Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 60th Weekly Dose of Optimism.
Packy and I will be together down the shore this weekend celebrating our mo=
m=E2=80=99s REDACTED birthday. She=E2=80=99s the best mom in the world. Hap=
py birthday momma!
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 Write of Passage [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/06d704ef-7b57-414e-b881-c4e3059e0f88?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Speaking of our mom, we have a fun recent story about her and today=E2=80=
=99s sponsor, Write of Passage [ https://substack.com/redirect/06d704ef-7b5=
7-414e-b881-c4e3059e0f88?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Unbeknownst to us, she attended WoP's recent live sessi=
on with Cultural Tudor. At some point during the end of the session, David =
Perell mentioned Packy=E2=80=99s name as a =E2=80=9Csuccess story.=E2=80=9D=
 Our mom, of course, proudly wrote into the Zoom chat that she was Packy=E2=
=80=99s mom=E2=80=A6for all of the hundreds of attendees to see. Moms are f=
unny.
Anyway, registration for Write of Passage=E2=80=99s 11th Cohort [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/06d704ef-7b57-414e-b881-c4e3059e0f88?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is now officially open.=
 You can sign up here [ https://substack.com/redirect/06d704ef-7b57-414e-b8=
81-c4e3059e0f88?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ]. We=E2=80=99ve shared at length how the course totally transforme=
d Packy=E2=80=99s career trajectory and why publishing on the internet is s=
o powerful. We=E2=80=99ll leave it up to you to decide whether or not you=
=E2=80=99re ready to make the plunge.
P.S. I think we have to get our mom the Write of Passage course for her bir=
thday, right?
(1) Breakthrough Prize Announces 2024 Laureates in Life Sciences, Fundament=
al Physics, and Mathematics [ https://substack.com/redirect/0bfe1fd5-b5b7-4=
2c9-a505-3a4fbc5b966d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Science is an endless revolution. Diseases that looked unbeatable twenty ye=
ars ago can now be managed or cured. Our deepest physics theories explain t=
he world to staggering precision. And in the realm of mathematics, new idea=
s are reaching into the borderlands of the unknown.
Every year, the Breakthrough Prize, known as the =E2=80=9COscars of Science=
,=E2=80=9D awards $3 million prizes for advances in Life Sciences, Fundamen=
tal Physics, and Mathematics. It=E2=80=99s a slightly splashier Nobel, and =
a celebration of the people behind the types of breakthroughs we celebrate =
in the Weekly Dose.=20
We=E2=80=99re not smart enough to understand the contributions of the winne=
rs in Fundamental Physics (John Cardy and Alexander Zamolodchikov for their=
 work in quantum field physics) or Mathematics (Simon Brendle for his =E2=
=80=9Cseries of remarkable leaps in differential geometry), but =F0=9F=AB=
=A1 .
The results of the three winners in the Life Sciences category are more tan=
gible.=20
Sabine Hadida, Paul Negulescu and Fredrick Van Goor, three scientists at Ve=
rtex Pharmaceuticals (which we wrote about in our piece on Atomic AI [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/ecde91c2-62be-4f4d-a3ca-55e44096e2b2?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]), developed a trip=
le-drug combination, Trifakta, to fight cystic fibrosis. The disease impact=
s 100,000 people worldwide. A study published February this year showed tha=
t Trifakta can increase life expectancy from ~30 to over 80 years, or an av=
erage of 45.4 years.=20
Ellen Sidransky, Andrew Singleton, and Thomas Gasser shared a second award =
for the discovery of two genes, GBA1 and LRRK2, associated with the risk of=
 developing Parkinson=E2=80=99s Disease. Scientists now need to figure out =
how these genes cause the disease, and then how to, hopefully, stop them fr=
om doing so.=20
Carl June and Michel Sadelain won the third Life Sciences award for =E2=80=
=9Cdeveloping a CAR-T-cell immunotherapy treatment that stimulates patients=
=E2=80=99 own T cells to target and kill cancer cells,=E2=80=9D which can l=
ead to long-lasting remission for some cancers. Elliot [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/7a00e097-d4fe-4f0b-a7f4-58094d58677f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] has written about CAR-T [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/166ece88-ac1b-48c8-b649-f380daaab97f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for those who want t=
o learn more.=20
Humans rock. Congrats to the winners. As for the rest of you, you have one =
year until the 2025 Breakthrough Prize winners are announced, get to work.=
=20
(2) Webb Discovers Methane, Carbon Dioxide in Atmosphere of K2-18 b [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/a5f5c74a-4636-45d9-85f5-672c18a66fe5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From NASA
A new investigation with NASA=E2=80=99s James Webb Space Telescope into K2-=
18 b, an exoplanet 8.6 times as massive as Earth, has revealed the presence=
 of carbon-bearing molecules including methane and carbon dioxide. Webb=E2=
=80=99s discovery adds to recent studies suggesting that K2-18 b could be a=
 Hycean exoplanet, one which has the potential to possess a hydrogen-rich a=
tmosphere and a water ocean-covered surface.
Humans rock. What about non-humans? You=E2=80=99ve probably seen this image=
 go around a bit in the last couple of days. Journalist and self-proclaimed=
 UFOlogist, Jaime Maussan, exhibited =E2=80=9Ctwo mummified specimens of ex=
traterrestrial beings=E2=80=9D to the Mexican congress. Experts scoffed, bu=
t at least the presentation launched a thousand memes.
However, more credible space exploration organizations have released some e=
vidence that points towards life beyond our planet. NASA's James Webb Space=
 Telescope has detected carbon-bearing molecules, including methane and car=
bon dioxide, on the exoplanet K2-18 b, suggesting it may be a hycean (hydro=
gen-ocean) exoplanet with a hydrogen-rich atmosphere and potentially a wate=
r ocean surface. If the atmosphere is just the right thickness (too thick, =
and the greenhouse effect would make liquid oceans impossible, too thin, an=
d the water would freeze or evaporate), we may have discovered a habitable =
planet 124 light years away.=20
JWST may have also discovered inhabitants. Initial observations also hint a=
t the presence of dimethyl sulfide (DMS), a molecule that is only produced =
by microbial life on Earth.=20
The day after we got our hopes up about tiny aliens in Mexico, NASA dropped=
 the potential for even tinier bacteria aliens on K2-18 b. Good time for Sc=
ully=E2=80=99s reminder:=20
(3) Why Is It So Expensive to Build Stuff in America? [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/90d0c13f-7850-4357-b1ec-e920b8aa53fd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Derek Thompson [ https://substack.com/redirect/53ae6808-231f-4498-8b84-eb1f=
552528a5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ] for Plain English
So at a very high level, I would say it=E2=80=99s basically a case of we=E2=
=80=99ve steadily made it more and more difficult to build things in the U.=
S. with rules and regulations and that sort of thing, and have not had comm=
ensurate technology and productivity increases that have been able to offse=
t that. So the regulations and the difficulties and stuff like that just ki=
nd of adds more and more and more burdens over time, and there has not been=
 an offset technological improvement to counter it.
On the surface, that excerpt and the entire premise of this conversation be=
tween Derek Thompson and Brian Potter is not =E2=80=9Coptimistic.=E2=80=9D =
It=E2=80=99s an analysis of why it takes so long and is so expensive to bui=
ld things in America these days, at least vis-=C3=A0-vis earlier periods in=
 American history. Potter=E2=80=99s answer is pretty straightforward: regul=
atory burden has outpaced technological progress.
Implied in that explanation of the problem are two solutions: decrease regu=
latory burden or increase the pace of technological progress. We=E2=80=99re=
 not going to hold our breath on regulatory changes, but we (and Potter) ar=
e optimistic about some of the technological advancements in construction t=
hat could meaningfully increase the speed and/or decrease the cost of build=
ing things. Of note, Potter mentions advancements in material science, spec=
ifically in lumber =E2=80=94 growing wood more effectively and basically ge=
netically modifying out its blemishes.
(Yes, we know it=E2=80=99s crazy that we=E2=80=99re more optimistic about w=
ood technology than making a few common sense regulatory changes.)
(4) Nougat: Neural Optical Understanding for Academic Documents [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/3043b601-725f-4efd-8265-0ae940560b8c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Lukas Blecher [ https://substack.com/redirect/6387a430-46b9-4c4f-bd7f-3961c=
71acbc0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
], Guillem Cucurull [ https://substack.com/redirect/f19be172-95af-4042-8452=
-d306afcd7830?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ], Thomas Scialom [ https://substack.com/redirect/27110c3a-dc68-40ba-=
89b1-5db35f7d4102?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ], Robert Stojnic [ https://substack.com/redirect/aef3ae70-9078-4=
065-b32f-870b7555e8e0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Scientific knowledge is predominantly stored in books and scientific journa=
ls, often in the form of PDFs. However, the PDF format leads to a loss of s=
emantic information, particularly for mathematical expressions. We propose =
Nougat (Neural Optical Understanding for Academic Documents), a Visual Tran=
sformer model that performs an Optical Character Recognition (OCR) task for=
 processing scientific documents into a markup language, and demonstrate th=
e effectiveness of our model on a new dataset of scientific documents.
Facebook=E2=80=99s AI Research team strikes again.=20
The LLMs we all know and use today, like OpenAI, have largely been trained =
on data obtained from crawling the web, scraping Wikipedia, and a few other=
 digital-native sources of information. But there are billions or trillions=
 of high-quality tokens, currently frozen in textbook pixels [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/348f8ded-ef94-4941-8689-fa9e20e0a2b5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that are not LLM-ready =E2=
=80=94 think an out-of-print chemical engineering textbook or some other sc=
ientific document, heavy in mathematical expression, that has not been digi=
tized. All of that information would be super valuable to train LLMs on, es=
pecially as it pertains to producing LLMs that can tackle extremely complex=
 mathematical and sceintific questions. To date, that info has been locked =
in hard-to-read PDFs.
A new model, Nougat, aims to unlock the scientific knowledge in those docum=
ents by using an advanced form of Optical Character Recognition (OCR) for p=
rocessing scientific documents into a markup language, and thus becoming di=
gestible by LLMs. Its goal is to bridge the gap between human-readable docu=
ments and machine-readable text. The research team published Nougat=E2=80=
=99s results, which shows their approach has potential for not only extract=
ing text from PDFs, scanned papers, and texbooks.
(5) MDMA-assisted therapy for moderate to severe PTSD [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/9d1f1515-4d53-4bae-b3d8-227cc7aa1422?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Mitchell [ https://substack.com/redirect/33584c8d-93f7-478a-977c-8ed53701fa=
b8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] et =
al, Nature
These data suggest that MDMA-AT reduced PTSD symptoms and functional impair=
ment in a diverse population with moderate to severe PTSD and was generally=
 well tolerated.
Packy here. Most people think Richard Nixon was a dick because of Watergate=
=2E I think Richard Nixon was a dick be=
cause he passed the 1970 Controlled Su=
bstances Act as part of the War on Drugs and classified psychedelics Schedu=
le I substances.=20
Schedule I substances are considered to have a high potential for abuse, no=
 currently accepted medical use (in the United States), and are unsafe to u=
se even if under supervision by healthcare professionals. That classificati=
on killed research into psychedelics such as MDMA (added to the list in 198=
5), psilocybin, and LSD, despite the fact that these drugs don=E2=80=99t fi=
t the definition of Schedule I substances.=20
Fortunately, research has picked back up in recent years, especially for th=
e treatment of PTSD and treatment-resistant depression. In 2017, the FDA gr=
anted =E2=80=9Cbreakthrough therapy=E2=80=9D status to MDMA-assisted therap=
y as a treatment for PTSD.
This most recent research, from MAPS [ https://substack.com/redirect/780209=
8f-6f48-433d-b953-022b23775e0b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjml=
XXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], is the second of Phase 3 trials on the impact of =
MDMA plus talk therapy on PTSD. After one session, 9.4% of patients went in=
to remission. After three sessions, 46.2% of patients went into remission. =
Only 13.5% of people didn=E2=80=99t respond =E2=80=94 another 25% no longer=
 met the PTSD diagnostic criteria and another 15.3% had at least a 10 point=
 reduction in severity from baseline.=20
Interestingly, the placebo group also improved, with 21.4% going into remis=
sion after three sessions with the placebo plus therapy. But MDMA was the c=
lear winner. This New York Times  [ https://substack.com/redirect/15275af7-=
1684-4904-8257-b85ff4384d79?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]article [ https://substack.com/redirect/15275af7-1684-=
4904-8257-b85ff4384d79?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] has more details on the study and the results.
An astonishing 5% of American adults are affected by PTSD each year, and sa=
dly, many believe that suicide is the only way out. MAPS is now planning to=
 submit the results to the FDA as part of its application to market MDMA + =
talk therapy as a treatment for PTSD. If approved, it will provide PTSD suf=
ferers with a real alternative.=20
We need more psychedelic treatments approved ASAP. This is a great step.=20
(Bonus) Lithium discovery in US volcano could be biggest deposit ever found=
 [ https://substack.com/redirect/58310230-8f1d-41f0-9982-83205ecb290b?j=3De=
yJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Anthony King [ https://substack.com/redirect/943ffb14-ad4f-449d-ac1f-3f1389=
feb62f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
 for Chemistry World
Even if this estimation is high due to variations in sediment thickness and=
/or Li grade, the Li inventory contained in McDermitt caldera sediments wou=
ld still be on par with, if not considerably larger than, the 10.2 MT of Li=
 inventory estimated to be contained in brines beneath the Salar de Uyuni i=
n Bolivia, previously considered the largest Li deposit on Earth.
Packy again. I was fired up for this one when I saw it =E2=80=94 the world=
=E2=80=99s largest lithium reserves discovered right in our backyard! =F0=
=9F=87=BA=F0=9F=87=B8=F0=9F=94=8B=F0=9F=87=BA=F0=9F=87=B8=F0=9F=94=8B=F0=9F=
=87=BA=F0=9F=87=B8=F0=9F=94=8B=F0=9F=A6=85
Earlier this week, a story from Chemistry World suggesting that researchers=
 had just discovered the world=E2=80=99s largest lithium reserves on in a v=
olcanic crater on the Nevada-Oregon border swept (at least my little corner=
 of) the internet. This was big news because the world is going to need a l=
ot of lithium-ion batteries for electric vehicles and energy storage, but C=
hina controls most of the world=E2=80=99s lithium production and a growing =
percentage of the raw material. Home-grown lithium would mean both more res=
ources and a more stable supply chain.=20
Big time. I was getting ready to go full-steam on that story, then I did a =
little digging.=20
The article was based on an August 30th paper in Science Advances titled Hy=
drothermal enrichment of lithium in intracaldera illite-bearing claystones =
[ https://substack.com/redirect/69310016-d156-4f48-b8b6-9eb5b1835004?j=3Dey=
J1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Some light =
reading and footnote clicking showed that the headline-making 20-40 million=
 ton estimate was based on a 2020 paper in  [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/137c74b2-d1d0-4dbf-ba67-49b360ee1e05?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlN=
uaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]Minerals [ https://substack.com/redirect/137=
c74b2-d1d0-4dbf-ba67-49b360ee1e05?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] by Stephen Castor and Christopher Henry, and th=
at people have known about the McDermitt caldera deposits for decades. They=
=E2=80=99ve even mined sections of the McDermitt caldera.=20
What the August 30th paper, from Lithium Americas Corp., which is developin=
g the site, showed was that, =E2=80=9CThe unique lithium enrichment of illi=
te at Thacker Pass resulted from secondary lithium- and fluorine-bearing hy=
drothermal alteration of primary neoformed smectite-bearing sediments.=E2=
=80=9D Essentially, it put forward a theory as to how the rarer lithium-pac=
ked illite clay formed. Very cool, but not the world-altering discovery its=
 been made out to be.=20
The good news here, as far as I can tell, is that this clay is packed with =
lithium (1.3 - 2.4 weight % of Li versus 0.4 weight % of Li in the more com=
mon magnesium smectite), and it=E2=80=99s in a sweet spot: close enough to =
the surface to avoid having to dig up too much rock, but deep enough that i=
t hasn=E2=80=99t weathered away yet.=20
Lithium Americas Corp. is going to begin mining the site in 2026. At the sa=
me time, we=E2=80=99ll need to ramp our lithium refining capabilities to tu=
rn all the raw material into batteries.=20
With the word of caution that the story isn=E2=80=99t exactly as incredible=
 as it sounds =E2=80=94 we didn=E2=80=99t just discover all of this lithium=
 =E2=80=94 the larger point is exciting. There have been fears about our ab=
ility to mine and refine all of the lithium we need for the energy transiti=
on in an environmentally friendly way. But the market demand upped our expl=
oration game, and it seems as if we=E2=80=99ve found a deposit in America t=
hat=E2=80=99s both huge and easier to mine than other sources. We still nee=
d to figure out refining capacity, but that=E2=80=99s a solvable problem.=
=20
Just as we figured out fracking when people were calling for peak oil, we=
=E2=80=99ll figure out new ways to turn clay into batteries, because people=
 rock.=20
As Robert Zubrin wrote in The Case for Nukes:
Our resources are growing, not shrinking, because resources are defined by =
human creativity. In fact, there are no such things as =E2=80=9Cnatural res=
ources.=E2=80=9D There are only natural raw materials. It is human ingenuit=
y that turns natural raw materials into resources.
Malthus keeps losing.=20
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tu=
esday.
Thanks for reading,
Dan + Packy

